[[File:University building, Drummond Street - geograph.org.uk - 1352882.jpg|thumb|The building which houses the university's School of GeoSciences Institute of Geography at High School Yards, which was once part of the [[Edinburgh Royal Infirmary]]]]
The '''University of Edinburgh School of GeoSciences,''' is a school within the College of Science and Engineering, which was formed in 2002<ref name="history">[http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/geosciences/about/history], School of Geosciences website, accessed 2011-07-26.</ref> by the merger of four departments.<ref name="merger">[http://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/public/theschool.html], School of Geosciences website, accessed 2011-07-26. The school was formed by the merger of the Institute of Ecology and Resource Management, Department of Geography, Department of Geology and Geophysics, and Institute for Meteorology.</ref> It is split between the [[King's Buildings]] and the Central Area of the university. The institutes of Ecological Sciences and Earth Science are located at the King's Buildings, whilst the Institute of Geography is located on [[Drummond Street, Edinburgh|Drummond Street]] in the Central Area.<ref>http://www.docs.scieng.ed.ac.uk/office/undergraduate/school-meetings-for-new-undergraduate-students-2010.pdf</ref> In 2013 the department was ranked 8th best place to study Geography in the country by ''[[The Guardian]]'' University Rankings, down from 2nd in 2006.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2012/may/22/university-guide-geography-environmental-studies University guide 2013: Geography and environmental studies. ''The Guardian''] (accessed 10 May 2014)</ref>

The school is ranked as one of the best in the UK for Earth Sciences. A 2008 [[Research Assessment Exercise]] assessment ranked the "Earth Systems and Environmental Science" department as the best in the UK by number of world leading research and staff.<ref name="degrees">[http://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/public/theschool.html], School of GeoSciences website, accessed 2011-07-26.</ref><ref name="research">[http://www.nature.com/news/2008/081229/full/457013a/box/1.html], Graph from Nature article entitled "Good grades, but who gets the cash?" Published 29/12/2008, corrected 14/01/2009 and accessed 2011-07-26.</ref> Its Geography department was ranked 15th in the world according to the 2015 QS rankings.<ref>[http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/arts-humanities/geography QS World University Rankings - Topuniversities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

There are over 1100 undergraduate students and 250 postgraduate students in the School of GeoSciences.<ref name="about">[http://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/public/], School of GeoSciences "about us" page, accessed 2011-07-26.</ref> There are also around 100 research and teaching staff within the school.<ref name="about" />

The School collaborates with the [[University of Edinburgh Business School]] and the School of Economics, to offer a [[Carbon management|Carbon Management]] MSc degree, the first in the world, which has students from over 20 countries.<ref name="carbon management">[http://www.business-school.ed.ac.uk/msc/carbon-management] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128051042/http://www.business-school.ed.ac.uk/msc/carbon-management |date=28 January 2010 }} School of Business course overview, Accessed 2011-07-26</ref> The school also has exchange programmes though the [[Erasmus]] programme, in addition to universities in Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand.<ref>[http://www.ed.ac.uk/studying/undergraduate/degrees?id=0,8&cw_xml=subject.php Degree finder | Undergraduate study<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

The head of the School of GeoSciences is currently Professor Alexander W Tudhope. Famous recent alumni of the School include former [[BP]] chief executive [[Tony Hayward]].<ref name="Tony Hayward">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-10754710], Accessed 2011-07-26.</ref> Former [[Rector of the University of Edinburgh|Rector of the university]] [[Peter McColl]] matriculated at one of the predecessors, the Department of Geography.<ref>[http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/all-news/rector-120212 New Rector confirmed | News | News and events<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Competition for entry is highly selective, in 2010, the School received 2221 applications, but only 275 offers were made, representing a 16.9% of an applicant receiving an offer.<ref name="admissions">[http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/student-recruitment/admissions-advice/admissions-statistics], School of Geosciences admission statistics, accessed 2011-07-26.</ref> The school currently offers 11 undergraduate courses and a range of postgraduate degrees.<ref name="degrees"/>

